we are going to be vacinated. Groeger was very much worried about the "shots" and
would have backed out t his morning if I hadn't dug him out of his room and drag-
ed him down to
the ship doctor telling him that I had promised Mr. Trippe that I
would see to it that we both were vacinated, etc.
You may have noticed some improvement in my typewriting, but whether
you have or not, I am very glad to have the machine along because it would be
very difficult to write long hand with the boat rolling the way it is. They say
this weather will last all the way over. You see we follow the great circle
course which takes us far north, in fact we will be within sight (with reasonably
good visability) of the Alutian Islands for two or three days.
Groeger and I sit at a table with the Chief Executive Officer who is
second in command and whose duties on board ship correspond to those of a general
manager in busines concerns. He has been so busy that we have seen him only once
the rest of the time he has been what the Chinese steward who serves our table
calls "top side" which I assume means in Mi dwest landlubber language "up stairs!
His name is Claxton and he looks like an English character on the Comic Opera
stage, but he is very agreable and I
imagine rather nice if you could ever get
under his conservat ive skin. While I am writing t his we are ploughing through
the biggest waves I've ever seen, and just to add to the fun also a snow storm
of blizzard proportions. Its nice and warm in my stateroom. Groeger has just come
in to tell me that he feels sort of sick from his innouculation, but I guess its
not very serious for his next comment was "When do we eat" an indoor pastime at
which I have found him moat proficient. The food is very good and the menu like
most ship menus includes every thing from soup to nuts. Groeger has not take n
many finesses to
date. He is very good company and tells some amusing stories
about his experiences on sailing vessels, in flying operations at Havana and in
Brazil where he has been in charge for Pan American. He has promised to get me
a Honey Bear for Bo. Or maybe we had better give the Honey Be ar to Ralph as
Groeger says it is Impossible to "housebreak" them. He said that he had one for
a year in which time he trained him to get his slippers and do a lot of tricks
but he was not able to teach him not
to do certain tricks and had to ultimately
make a choice between Mrs. Groeger or the Honey Bear. So the H.B. got the air.
Must stop now for Lunch. Personal message follows, and I'll write
again toon.
